-- French Stocks: Alstom, Lafarge, Renault, Ubisoft, Maurel & Prom Are Active
-- B y   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 2010-11-05T17:01:32Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-05/french-stocks-alstom-lafarge-renault-ubisoft-maurel-prom-are-active.html
France’s benchmark CAC Index was
little changed at 3,916.73 at the close in Paris after rallying
1.9 percent yesterday. The gauge has risen 2.2 percent this
week. The broader SBF 120 Index gained 0.1 percent today.  The following is a list of companies whose shares either
rose or fell in the French capital. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  Alstom SA  (ALO FP) dropped 4 percent to 34.38 euros after
Societe Generale SA lowered its recommendation for the world’s
third-largest power-equipment maker to “sell” from “hold.”  Axa SA  (CS FP) gained 2.1 percent to 13.72 euros, a second
day of gains. Australia’s AMP Ltd., whose bid for Axa Asia
Pacific Holdings Ltd. was rebuffed in favor of National
Australia Bank Ltd.’s higher offer, is in talks with Axa for
another potential bid for the Melbourne-based wealth manager.  Australian regulators blocked National Australia Bank’s
A$13.3 billion ($13.5 billion) agreed offer for Axa Asia Pacific
in September, citing competition concerns.  Bureau Veritas SA  (BVI FP) jumped 3.4 percent to 57.67
euros. The world’s second-largest goods inspection company
posted a 16 percent rise in third-quarter revenue to 739 million
euros, helped by exchange rates and acquisitions.  The company said it expects a “slight improvement in
adjusted operating margin on an organic basis,” and reiterated
its target for second-half revenue growth.  Lafarge SA  (LG FP) declined 1.6 percent to 44.53 euros,
paring two days of gains, after the world’s biggest cement maker
reported an 8 percent decline in third-quarter profit to 372
million euros.  Scor SA  (SCR FP) rose 4.4 percent to 18.49 euros as
France’s biggest reinsurer posted an 18 percent rise in third-
quarter net income rose to 111 million euros ($156.4 million).  Societe Television Francaise 1  (TFI FP) gained 2.4 percent
to 12.76 euros after JPMorgan Chase & Co. raised its
recommendation for the owner of France’s most-watched TV channel
to “overweight” from “neutral.”  Ubisoft Entertainment SA  (UBI FP) rallied 4.4 percent to
9.74 euros after Europe’s biggest video game producer said it
acquired Quazal Technologies.  To contact the reporters on this story:
